\f1\b\fs52 \cb3 The Empathy Gap\cb1 \

\f0\b0\fs36 \cb3 When I first started on a diet, I found it hard to imagine myself eating unhealthy food.\cb1 \
\cb3 But soon after, when I was hungry and a plate of delicious char kway teow was in front of me, I gave in to temptation. While devouring the noodles, I found it hard to imagine myself avoiding unhealthy food \'97 the complete opposite of what I had experienced previously.\'a0\cb1 \
\cb3 Maybe you may have had a similar experience yourself, but this is a classic case of the empathy gap. This is a cognitive bias where people underestimate their emotional and mental states in different scenarios.\'a0\cb1 \
\cb3 For example, we overestimate our ability to act properly in a stressful event when we are not stressed, or we struggle to understand why our spouse acted in a certain way when he or she was angry.\'a0\cb1 \

\f1\b \cb3 How is this related to investing?\cb1 \

\f0\b0 \cb3 We always hear that we should buy low and sell high. When calm and rational, we think that this can be easily done. However, in a recession, we may act in a different way, and find it much harder to follow this advice.\cb1 \
\cb3 The advice is known by many, but followed by few. There is a gap between our emotional states when we are in and out of a recession.\'a0\cb1 \

\f1\b\fs52 \cb3 Overconfidence Bias\cb1 \

\f0\b0\fs36 \cb3 Are you a below-average driver, an average driver, or an above-average driver?\cb1 \
\cb3 This question had been posed as a survey to many people before. The strange fact is that the majority of the respondents indicated that they were above-average drivers. This is a classic case of how everyone thinks they are better than the rest, which means that most of these people are wrong in their beliefs.\'a0\cb1 \
\cb3 This sense of over-optimism and over-confidence bias seems to play a huge role in our lives. Several experiments have shown that we tend to believe that we have much more control and that situations are much rosier than they actually are.\'a0\cb1 \
\cb3 Experiments have shown that individuals who had certain parts of their brains related to emotions impaired, were able to make much better rational decisions, and were not over-confident of their own abilities. Others have concluded that depressed people were more realistic, as they were less over-confident and over-optimistic in assessing situations.\cb1 \

\f1\b \cb3 How does this relate to investing?\cb1 \

\f0\b0 \cb3 Who doesn\'92t like confident investors? The folly of the over-confidence bias should remind us that we may be overestimating our abilities, as well as the situation around us.\cb1 \
\cb3 Perhaps we could be too over-confident on the performance of a particular stock or investment strategy, or the management of a company could be too over-confident in how their company might perform in the future.\cb1 \
